# .yamtamignore — suppress known/accepted YAMTAM audit findings
#
# Format:
#   RULE_ID                         suppress this rule everywhere
#   RULE_ID:path/to/file.yml        suppress only for this specific file
#
# Copy this file to .yamtamignore in your project root.
# Lines starting with # are comments.
#
# Rule IDs are shown in audit output, e.g. [HIGH] AC001 ...
#
# Example entries (uncomment and adjust to your project):

# CI003:.github/workflows/deploy.yml   # auto-deploy accepted — gated by branch protection
# SH008:scripts/legacy.sh              # false positive — rm -rf is on test fixtures dir only
# ENV001                               # suppress across all files — no .env files in this repo
# MCP001:.mcp.json                     # full filesystem access is intentional for this tool

# Tip: keep suppressions minimal. If a finding is a real risk, fix it.
# Document the reason — the comment is your audit trail.
